<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?>
<!--
  Coverlet / XPlat-Code-Coverage configuration for the CNAS „Protecția Socială" solution.

  Why this file exists (CLAUDE.md §3.4 / TOR R0007):
    The line-coverage gate in `.github/workflows/ci.yml` (currently 85% — ratcheted up
    from 80 in iter-143, final TOR target 90% per UAT 005 / R2702) is meaningful only
    when the coverage denominator excludes code we do not author and cannot meaningfully
    test:
    EF Core migrations (auto-generated rewrites of model snapshots), `*.Designer.cs`
    (auto-generated by the EF designer), `*.Generated.cs` (any source-generator output),
    and the SDK-emitted `GlobalUsings.g.cs`. Without these exclusions, every new
    migration drops the apparent coverage by tens of thousands of generated lines and
    forces engineers either to lower the threshold (defeating the ratchet) or to write
    nonsensical tests against generated code.

  How CI consumes this:
    The `Run tests with coverage` step in `.github/workflows/ci.yml` passes the
    settings flag pointing at this file. Local runs can do the same by passing
    the `XPlat Code Coverage` collector together with a `settings` argument
    naming this file (see the CI workflow's invocation for the exact form).

  How to extend:
    * To exclude another generated source family, add a glob to `<ExcludeByFile>`.
    * To exclude an assembly entirely (e.g. a future scaffolding project), add it to
      `<Exclude>` using Coverlet's `[Assembly]Type.Method` syntax (`[Cnas.Ps.*Foo]*`).
    * DO NOT add production code to the exclusions just to make the gate green; fix
      the coverage gap with a test instead. That is the whole point of the ratchet.
-->
<RunSettings>
  <DataCollectionRunSettings>
    <DataCollectors>
      <DataCollector friendlyName="XPlat code coverage">
        <Configuration>
          <!-- Assembly-level filters: Coverlet syntax is `[Assembly]Type`.
               Excluding the migrations namespace catches both the timestamped Up/Down
               classes and their companion .Designer.cs snapshots regardless of folder. -->
          <Exclude>[*]Cnas.Ps.Infrastructure.Persistence.Migrations.*</Exclude>
          <ExcludeByAttribute>GeneratedCodeAttribute,CompilerGeneratedAttribute</ExcludeByAttribute>
          <!-- File-glob filters: belt-and-braces guard for generated-code sources the
               assembly filter cannot reach (e.g. the SDK's GlobalUsings.g.cs is emitted
               into obj/ but its symbols flow into the assembly under various namespaces). -->
          <ExcludeByFile>**/Migrations/**/*.cs,**/*.Designer.cs,**/*.Generated.cs,**/GlobalUsings.g.cs,**/AssemblyInfo.cs</ExcludeByFile>
          <Format>cobertura</Format>
          <!-- Skip auto-properties so trivial { get; set; } scaffolding isn't counted.
               They still ship in the assembly, but their "lines" are synthetic IL that
               distort the denominator on data-class-heavy projects (Cnas.Ps.Contracts). -->
          <SkipAutoProps>true</SkipAutoProps>
        </Configuration>
      </DataCollector>
    </DataCollectors>
  </DataCollectionRunSettings>
</RunSettings>
